    abstract = {From a historical-structural perspective, the article analyzes the revolutionary and post-revolutionary conditions that have made possible or impossible the property rights of the indigenous and Afro-descendants of the Caribbean Coast and the peasants of all Nicaragua. This shows that Nicaragua has experienced two different patterns of social formations and land rights: (a) the Sandinista authoritarian corporatist Revolution with mixed public-private capital that forcibly recognizes indigenous communal property and undertakes an agrarian reform concentrating land in the hands of the State that obliges landless peasants to form agricultural cooperatives and landless peasants to form credit and service cooperatives (1980–1990); (b) the post-Sandinista revolution with hybrid or authoritarian and neoliberal governments, which despite the titling of indigenous-Afro-descendant territories and the agrarian counter-reform that distributed lands among the peasantry, opened communal and peasant properties to the market. © 2021 CALACS.},
