    abstract = {Agricultural supply chain management is of increasing interest from practical and academic stand-points, where the sourcing strategy issue has long plagued purchasers. Further, the special attributes of fresh agriculture products and unpredictable emergencies make agricultural supply chain likely subject to supply chain disruption risk, and these disruptions are extreme, although occurring with low frequencies, which leads to the shortage of downstream enterprises and customers, even severely reduces the performance of whole agricultural supply chain. The paper studies on the supply disruption risk problem faced by the supermarket’s purchasing. Assume a two-level option-based agricultural supply chain, which is consisted of the agricultural cooperative and the supermarket. Through numerical examples, compare the performance of different purchasing strategies (single, traditional dual, dual based on option contracts) under the setting of supply disruptions. The results show which under the supply disruption, the dual sourcing outperforms the single sourcing; the dual sourcing with option contracts brings flexibility, and maximizes the profit of the supermarket, which is the better purchasing strategy to prevent and avoid the disruption of a supply chain, providing decision-making reference for supermarket. © Foundation Environmental Protection & Research-FEPR.},
