    abstract = {Information and communication technology usage has brought a lot of transformation into the Nigerian economy. The most recent is the introduction of mobile and e-banking into the banking industry and this has extended accessibility of banking facility to many of the previously unbanked Nigerians. This study examined the extent to which mobile phones have aided financial services among farming households in rural southwest Nigeria. Data for this study were collected from a random sample of 360 farming households in Ekiti and Osun States. Descriptive analysis of data on respondents' socioeconomic characteristics showed that the farmers are aging (average age is 55 years) with only about one-third (34.7 per cent) having tertiary education. Respondents' distribution by services conducted on their mobile phones indicated transfer of recharge cards which are later converted into cash as the most patronized. Important correlates of mobile phones usage as mobile banks include age, years of formal education, membership of cooperative societies, household size and access to power (electricity). © 2013 Macmillan Publishers Ltd.},
