    abstract = {The study was undertaken in the Sirsa district of Haryana state, which was selected purposively. A multistage sampling technique was adopted for selection of district, blocks, village and finally pearl millet growers. As per objective of the study, the 30 heads of pearl millet cultivating farmers were taken from each selected village to make the sample size of 120 farmers. The study reveals that the constraints related to inputs like high price of weedicides, pesticides and fungicides and lack of irrigation facilities were very serious in nature. Failure of crop due to unfavourable weather conditions and using of seeds without treatments were very serious and lack of knowledge about time of application and recommended dose of fertilizers were serious constraints in production. In case of marketing of produce, the constraints like distress sale due to immediate need for money was very serious, whereas lack of warehousing facilities, lack of procurement of produce by government, low support price of produce and lack of co-operative organization for marketing of produce were found to be serious. Lack of demonstrations and trials of pearl millet production were considered to be very serious constraints by the respondents. The serious constraints identified by the farmers in case of technical guidance were lack of guidance for controlling insects-pests and application of pesticides and fungicides, lack of guidance for chemical weed control and chemical weedicides, lack of guidance for seed treatment, lack of knowledge of current advances for pearl millet production and lack of knowledge of recommended dose of chemical fertilizers. To overcome these constraints, efforts should be made to provide full package of practices about pearl millet production to the farmers well in advance by the extension personnel by visiting their fields.},
