    abstract = {During surveys conducted in the fields at village Siar in district Ludhiana of Punjab, India, crops were found infested with four rodent species, namely, Bandicota bengalensis, Rattus maltada, Tatera indica and Mus spp. Survey of rodent control practices by farmers revealed that farmers (n=20) carry out rodent control as a regular practice but 80% of them, depending upon the level of damage to crops, conduct symptomatic control treatments with zinc phosphide. However, in general they expressed dissatisfaction about the effectiveness of zinc phosphide baiting for which the major causes were found to be the lack of pre-baiting, use of incorrect methods of bait preparation, multiple baitings of zinc phosphide at short intervals and non-removal of left over rodenticide bait and dead rodents after the treatments leading to poison-bait shyness and individual rather than campaign approach to rodent control. Village level training and field demonstrations organized with the help of three organizations of the village, namely, the Pendu Vikas Ate Mulazam Bhalai Sanstha Sangh, the Siar Pandher Co-operative Society and the Gram Panchayat, to an assembly of about fifty farmers resulted in partial success as determined on the basis of post-training survey of these parameters from a sample of 20 farmers in adoption of regular rodent control at recommended timings (45%) and pre-baiting before the use of zinc phosphide (25%) with correct method of bait preparation (60%). However, only three farmers (15%) treated rodents in the uncultivated and wasteland areas adjoining their crop fields and only one (5%) organized rodent control on large areas along with his neighbours. No farmer could be convinced for removing left over rodenticide bait and dead rodents from the fields after the treatments. Farmer's field demonstration trials were carried out at four fields each of 7.5 hectare size in different blocks of the village. Rodenticide treatments under experts' supervision in the fields designated as maintenance (M) fields resulted in 94.94% rodent control with 0.005% bromadiolone followed by 2% zinc phosphide baiting in rice fields and 85.42% with 2% zinc phosphide followed by 0.0375% Racumin baiting in wheat fields. With the absence of the expert during the treatment in N1 fields with free supply of rodenticide and education and training, rodent control success decreased non-significantly which further decreased significantly without the free supply of rodenticides as in N2 fields both during the kharif and rabi seasons. The reference fields (R) had more rodent damage than in the treated fields. This comparative study revealed that for success of rodent control at farmer's fields not only the education and training of the farmers but the availability of the rodenticides are the critical factors.},
