    abstract = {Since the early 1980s, privately owned Savings and Credit Co-operative Societies (SACCS) have grown rapidly in Swaziland because commercial loans are either inaccessible or too costly, while public financial agencies failed to deliver the services needed by small borrowers (Matsebula, 1996). SACCS serve a wide range of clients including the poor and the self-employed as well as formal sector employees, and have shown a potential to enhance financial and economic development in the country. They provide insurance cover as well as non-exclusive starting loans to small enterprises that may eventually gain access to bigger bank loans to finance expansion. Such 'linking strategies have the potential of overcoming problems of formal banks in replicating the techniques of informal financial intermediaries as well as the lack of resources among the informal or semi-formal financial sectors which preclude them from serving their clients on a large scale' (Schoombee, 1998:354). In the linking process, semi-formal financial intermediaries may assist banks in the monitoring, supervision and recovery of loans (Sanderatne, 1992). The study utilises survey data covering a sample of six societies, and argues that the SACCS' organisational structures, operating mechanisms, staff training and regulatory and advisory assistance from the Swaziland Association of Savings and Credit Co-operative Societies are the key factors for success. The article is organised as follows. Background information on the evolution and economic significance of SACCS in Swaziland is followed by an analysis of the survey data, focusing on their outreach and financial viability. The reasons for their success and the story of one society (Asikhutulisane) are then analysed before summarising the findings.},
