    abstract = {The governments in the Czech Republic, Hungary and Slovakia considered privatization the most important prerequisite for higher efficiency in the agricultural sector. The privatization process of the former state and collective farms, thousands of hectares in size, has been implemented predominantly by way of decollectivization, restitution and compensation as well as by direct privatization following decomposition into smaller entities. This procedure, though leading to a fragmentation of ownership, has not resulted in fragmented operation here, due to the dominance of new market-conforming smaller cooperatives and other types of corporations. In addition, most new small owners leased their land to the new agricultural cooperatives, though currently the share of small-scale farming especially in Hungary is growing. These new entities, extending over hundreds of hectares, have been mostly owned by managers holding important positions already in the previous political regime and thus experienced in large-scale operation. Consequently the old-new management is able to cope with the new circumstances in the transformed farms, which are still large enough to utilize economies of scale in production. Altogether, over 90% of the agricultural land in the CEFTA is now in private hands. Other crucial reform steps related to farming were massive cuts in agrarian subsidies and the liberalization of agro-food markets and of prices as well. Although the bulk of the institutional transformation of CEFTA agriculture has been completed, problems still to be solved are constituted mainly by the lack of market institutions such as a credit system related to the land market. The urgently needed existence of the land market would generate land prices that can serve as a guideline for borrowers and lenders regarding feasible mortgage values.},
