    abstract = {Akella and Greenbaum provided evidence from the savings and loan industry that the more diffuse ownership structures associated with mutuality exhibit greater agency cost through the expansion of inputs and outputs beyond profit-maximizing levels. Not-for-profit firms, in general, and credit unions, in particular, are characterized both by extreme diffusion of ownership and imprecise objectives. Using a model similar to that of Akella and Greenbaum, we hypothesize and test how the common bonds under which credit unions operate act in some instances as an exogenous force constraining managerial behavior in the absence of market controls.},
